VALUES
(42, 22, 65, 54, 1, 13, 14, 'blasphemously spake they against him', 'Connection of Blasphemy and Mercy', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of blasphemy, with Luke 22:65 noting blasphemous speech against Jesus and 1 Timothy 1:13 referencing a blasphemer who received mercy. This connection highlights the transformative power of grace in response to wrongdoing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 66, 40, 27, 1, 1, 'the elders of the people and the chief priests', 'Council Against Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of the chief priests and elders to plot against Jesus. They highlight the formal assembly and intent to take action against him, indicating a shared narrative moment.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 66, 41, 15, 1, 1, NULL, 'Morning Council Meeting', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of the chief priests, elders, and scribes in the morning to discuss Jesus. This connection highlights the continuity of events leading to Jesus'' delivery to Pilate.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 66, 44, 22, 5, 5, 'elders of the people and the chief priests', 'Connection of Elders and Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the elders and the high priest in their respective contexts. In Luke, the elders and chief priests convene to judge Jesus, while in Acts, Paul references the high priest and elders as authorities who sanctioned his actions.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 66, 40, 5, 22, 22, 'led him into their council', 'Connection of Judgment and Council', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of judgment and the council. In Luke, the council is where Jesus is led for judgment, while in Matthew, being in danger of the council relates to anger and insults among brothers.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 66, 44, 4, 25, 28, NULL, 'Gathering of Rulers', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of rulers against Jesus. In Luke, the elders and chief priests come together, while in Acts, Herod, Pontius Pilate, and others are described as gathered against the Lord and His Christ.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 66, 43, 18, 28, 28, 'as soon as it was day', 'Jesus'' Trial Proceedings', 'Both passages emphasize the early timing of Jesus'' trial. Luke mentions the gathering of the council at daybreak, while John notes that it was early when Jesus was led to judgment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 66, 19, 2, 1, 3, 'led him into their council', 'Counsel Against the Anointed', 'This connection highlights the gathering of rulers in Luke 22:66, paralleling the kings and rulers taking counsel against the Lord''s anointed in Psalms 2:1-3. Both passages emphasize a collective opposition to divine authority.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 67, 40, 11, 3, 5, 'Art thou the Christ?', 'Connection of Messianic Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the question of Jesus'' identity as the Christ. In Luke, Jesus suggests that revealing his identity would not lead to belief, while in Matthew, he points to his miraculous works as evidence of his messianic role.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 67, 40, 26, 63, 68, 'Art thou the Christ? tell us.', 'Connection of Christ''s Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the question of Jesus'' identity as the Christ. In Luke, Jesus indicates that revealing his identity would not lead to belief, while in Matthew, he affirms it directly, leading to accusations of blasphemy.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 67, 41, 14, 61, 66, 'Art thou the Christ?', 'Christ''s Identity and Response', 'Both passages emphasize the question of Jesus'' identity as the Christ. In Luke, Jesus indicates that revealing this truth would not lead to belief, while in Mark, he directly affirms his identity, leading to condemnation. This connection highlights the tension between acknowledgment and disbelief.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 67, 42, 16, 31, 31, 'ye will not believe', 'Belief and Persuasion Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of disbelief in both passages. In Luke 22:67, the question of belief is posed, while Luke 16:31 emphasizes that even miraculous events will not persuade those who do not heed prior revelations.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 67, 43, 5, 39, 47, 'If I tell you, ye will not believe', 'Connection of Belief and Testimony', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of belief in Christ and the rejection of His testimony. In Luke, Jesus indicates that revealing His identity will not lead to belief, while in John, He points out that the scriptures testify of Him, yet many refuse to come to Him for life.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 67, 43, 8, 43, 45, 'if I tell you, ye will not believe', 'Understanding and Belief', 'This connection highlights the theme of disbelief in both passages. In Luke, Jesus indicates that revealing his identity will not lead to belief, while in John, he addresses the inability to understand his words due to their rejection of truth.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 68, 42, 20, 3, 7, 'ye will not answer me', 'Authority and Questioning', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of questioning authority. In Luke 22:68, the speaker anticipates a lack of response, paralleling the evasive reasoning of the questioners in Luke 20:3-7. This connection highlights the tension between authority and accountability.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 68, 42, 20, 41, 44, NULL, 'Connection of Authority and Identity', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority and identity in relation to Jesus and David. Both passages emphasize the questioning of Jesus'' identity and his relationship to David, showcasing the complexities of his messianic role.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 69, 19, 110, 1, 1, 'sit on the right hand', 'Connection of Divine Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of sitting at God''s right hand, indicating a position of authority and power. Luke 22:69 directly references the Son of Man''s future exaltation, paralleling Psalms 110:1''s declaration of the Lord''s command to sit at His right hand.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 69, 27, 7, 13, 14, 'Son of man', 'Connection of the Son of Man', 'Both passages emphasize the authority and dominion of the ''Son of man.'' Luke 22:69 speaks of the Son of man sitting at God''s right hand, while Daniel 7:13-14 describes the Son of man receiving an everlasting kingdom.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 69, 41, 16, 19, 19, NULL, 'Connection of Christ''s Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the authority of the Son of Man as he is depicted sitting at the right hand of God. This connection highlights the fulfillment of Jesus'' statement about his exaltation after his resurrection.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 69, 58, 1, 3, 3, 'sit on the right hand', 'Connection of Divine Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of sitting at the right hand of divine authority. This connection highlights the exaltation of the Son, indicating His position of power and majesty.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 69, 40, 22, 44, 44, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of sitting at God''s right hand, indicating a position of authority. Luke 22:69 states the Son of man will sit on the right hand of God, while Matthew 22:44 quotes the Lord commanding the same position.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 69, 40, 26, 64, 64, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus'' Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the authority of the Son of man sitting at the right hand of power. This connection highlights the significance of Jesus'' position in relation to divine power and judgment.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
